}
}

\subtree{
\title{Phase 2: Phishlet Configuration}
\ol{
\li{Select or create a phishlet for the target service (e.g., Microsoft 365, Google Workspace):}
\li{Verify phishlet is active and SSL certificate is issued:}
\li{Create a lure URL for the phishing campaign:}
\li{Optionally configure a redirect URL for post-capture:}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Phase 3: Phishing Delivery}
\ol{
\li{Craft a pretext email with the lure URL embedded}
\li{Use GoPhish or manual SMTP for email delivery:}
\li{Implement URL masking or shortening if needed for link obfuscation}
\li{Deploy landing page with appropriate social engineering pretext}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Phase 4: Session Hijacking}
\ol{
\li{Monitor EvilGinx3 for captured sessions:}
\li{Extract captured session cookies from the session:}
\li{Import session cookies into a browser using a cookie editor extension:}
\li{Export cookies in JSON format}
\li{Use Cookie-Editor or EditThisCookie browser extension}
\li{Navigate to the target service to validate session hijack}
\li{Establish persistent access by creating application passwords or OAuth tokens}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Phase 5: Post-Access Activities}
\ol{
\li{Enumerate mailbox contents, contacts, and shared drives}
\li{Identify additional targets for lateral phishing}
\li{Check for access to connected cloud applications (SharePoint, Teams, OneDrive)}
\li{Document all captured credentials and access achieved}
}
}
}

